The HD 233604 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 233604 is a star with 1.5 times the mass of the Sun, and 10.9 times its radius. It is located 2762.73 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 2.4 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 233604 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 233604 system


HD 233604 b

HD 233604 b was discovered by the McDonald Observatory observatory, in 2013-06, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.75 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 233604 b is 2090.850 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 233604 b is 12.700 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 233604 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
